    <section class="faq-section">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <details>
        <summary>What are stocks?</summary>
        <p>Stocks represent fractional ownership in a company, allowing investors to participate in the company's growth and profits.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>How does the stock market work?</summary>
        <p>The stock market functions as an exchange where buyers and sellers trade shares of publicly held companies, driven by supply and demand.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>What are the different types of stocks?</summary>
        <p>Common types of stocks include growth, value, cyclical, mid-cap, large-cap, and small-cap stocks.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>What is a P/E ratio?</summary>
        <p>The Price-to-Earnings (P/E) ratio is a valuation metric that compares a company's current share price to its per-share earnings.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>How do I start evaluating stocks?</summary>
        <p>Beginners should look at key metrics like revenue growth, profitability, competitive advantage, debt levels, and valuation ratios like P/E.</p>
      </details>
